In finite dimensions, the spectral theorem says a symmetric matrix can be diagonalized by an orthogonal basis of eigenvectors. This planning principle transfers to functional analysis: to prove a compact self-adjoint operator on a Hilbert space has an orthonormal basis of eigenvectors, you mimic the finite-dimensional proof structure—use the variational characterization of eigenvalues instead of determinants, appeal to compactness for sequential limits instead of finite termination, and invoke the Riesz representation theorem where finite dimensions used matrix entries. Similarly, finite-dimensional orthogonal projections decompose a space as direct sums; infinite-dimensional projections decompose Hilbert spaces via completeness and orthogonal complements using the same conceptual roadmap. The analogy breaks down at infinite cardinality and convergence subtleties, but the proof skeleton—exploit symmetry, extract a special vector, iterate orthogonalization, appeal to compactness/completeness—remains transferable.